Step 4: deal with missing tavg

Problem: some rows have tmax and tmin but are missing tavg, while a few rows have tavg but no tmax or tmin.

We cannot recover tmax and tmin when they are missing, but we can approximate any missing tavg values by taking the average of tmax and tmin for that day.

Then we need to coalesce the two different kinds of tavg measurements: use the recorded tavg if present, otherwise use the approximated one.

Theres a nice function called coalesce() that will accomplish this for us. Given a set of vectors, it takes the first non-missing value at each position. For example

y <- c(1, 2, NA, NA, 5)
z <- c(NA, NA, 3, 4, 5)
coalesce(y, z)

[1] 1 2 3 4 5

Create a new variable tavg_approx that is the average of tmax and tmin, then coalesce tavg with tavg_approx.

satw <- satw %>% 
  mutate(tavg_approx = (tmax + tmin) / 2,
         tavg = coalesce(tavg, tavg_approx)) %>%  # Measured tavg first
  select(-tavg_approx)

knitr::kable(head(satw))

1946 Aug 1946-08-14 86 NA NA
1946 Aug 1946-08-15 85 NA NA
1946 Aug 1946-08-16 86 NA NA
1946 Aug 1946-08-17 86 NA NA
1946 Aug 1946-08-18 86 NA NA
1946 Aug 1946-08-19 86 NA NA

Step 5: monthly summary

Create a summary data set that is the mean of each t variable for each year and month.

satw_monthly <- satw %>% 
  group_by(year, month) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(starts_with("t")), mean, na.rm = TRUE)

knitr::kable(head(satw_monthly))

Step 6: pivot to longer format

For plotting, we will want to facet by the kind of temperature measurement (tmin, tavg, or tmax). That means we will need our data in long format with the variable names in a single new column and all the values in another new column.

After doing this, you can also reorder the new variable column so that the variables are plotted with tmin first and tmax last rather than alphabetically. Hint: mutate your new variable column using fct_reorder(), and reorder by the new value column. See this section of R4DS for an example.

satw_long <- satw_monthly %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("t"), names_to = "variable", values_to = "value")

# Reorder variables from smallest to largest
satw_long <- satw_long %>% 
  mutate(variable = fct_reorder(variable, value, .fun = mean, na.rm = TRUE))

knitr::kable(head(satw_long))
year month variable value
1946 Aug tavg 82.05556
1946 Aug tmax NaN
1946 Aug tmin NaN
1946 Sep tavg 78.11667
1946 Sep tmax 86.16667
1946 Sep tmin 70.06667

Step 7: tile plot of actual values

ggplot(satw_long, aes(x = month, y = year, fill = value)) + 
  geom_tile(color = "white") + 
  scale_fill_continuous_sequential("Heat", name = expression(Temperature~degree~C)) + 
  facet_wrap(~variable) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(1950, 2020, by = 5)) +
  coord_cartesian(expand = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Year") +
  guides(fill = guide_colorbar(frame.colour = "black", ticks.colour = "black")) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5),
        legend.key.width = unit(2, "cm"))

Yep looks about right. Pretty hot in the summer.

Step 8: calculate the temperature anomaly for each month and variable using a grouped mutate

satw_anom <- satw_long %>% 
  group_by(month, variable) %>% 
  mutate(anom = value - mean(value, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ungroup()

knitr::kable(head(satw_anom))

1946 Aug tmin NaN NaN

Step 9: tile plot of temperature anomalies

To get the diverging color scale right (centered at zero), find the largest absolute value in the new anomaly column, e.g.,

lim <- max(abs(satw_anom$anom), na.rm = TRUE)

Then use limits = c(-lim, lim) in your scale_fill_ function.

satw_anom <- satw_anom %>% 
  mutate(variable = fct_recode(variable, "T[min]" = "tmin", "T[avg]" = "tavg", "T[max]" = "tmax"))

# Find largest absolute anomaly so that we can center the color scale on zero
lim <- max(abs(satw_anom$anom), na.rm = TRUE)

ggplot(satw_anom, aes(x = month, y = year, fill = anom)) + 
  geom_tile(color = "white") + 
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "RdBu", 
                       limits = c(-lim, lim), # Here we provide limits to center the color scale on zero
                       name = expression(Anomaly~(degree*C))) + 
  facet_wrap(~variable, labeller = label_parsed) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(1950, 2020, by = 5)) +
  coord_cartesian(expand = FALSE) +
  guides(fill = guide_colorbar(ticks.colour = "black")) +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Year",
       title = "San Antonio Temperature Anomalies, 1946 - 2019",
       subtitle = "San Antonio International Airport",
       caption = "Data from the Global Historical Climatology Network (https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/ghcnd-data-access)") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5),
        legend.key.width = unit(2, "cm"))
